The first advanced single-celled, [[eukaryotes]] and multi-cellular life, [[Francevillian Group Fossil]]s, roughly coincides with the start of the accumulation of free oxygen.<ref name="albani">{{cite journal |last1=El Albani|first1= A. |last2=Bengtson|first2= S. |last3=Canfield|first3= D. E. |last4=Bekker|first4= A. |last5=Macchiarelli|first5= R.  |title=Large colonial organisms with coordinated growth in oxygenated environments 2.1 Gyr ago |journal=Nature |volume=466 |issue=7302 |pages=100–104 |date=2010 |pmid=20596019 |doi=10.1038/nature09166 |url=|bibcode = 2010Natur.466..100A |last6=Mazurier |first6=A.|last7=Hammarlund |first7=E. U. |last8=Boulvais |first8=P. |last9=Dupuy |first9=J.-J. |last10=Fontaine |first10=C. |last11=Fürsich |first11=F. T. |last12=Gauthier-Lafaye |first12=F. |last13=Janvier |first13=P. |last14=Javaux |first14=E.|last15=Ossa |first15=F. O. |last16=Pierson-Wickmann |first16=A.-C. |last17=Riboulleau |first17=A. |last18=Sardini |first18=P. |last19=Vachard |first19=D.|last20=Whitehouse |first20=M. |last21=Meunier |first21=A.}}</ref> This may have been due to an increase in the oxidized [[nitrate]]s that eukaryotes use, as opposed to [[cyanobacteria]].<ref name=Stanley/>{{rp|325}} It was also during the Proterozoic that the first [[symbiosis|symbiotic]] relationships between [[mitochondria]] (found in nearly all eukaryotes) and [[chloroplast]]s (found in [[plant]]s and some [[protist]]s only) and their hosts evolved.<ref name=Stanley/>{{rp|321–2}}

The blossoming of eukaryotes such as [[acritarch]]s did not preclude the expansion of cyanobacteria; in fact, [[stromatolites]] reached their greatest abundance and diversity during the Proterozoic, peaking roughly 1200 million years ago.<ref name=Stanley/>{{rp|321–3}}

Classically, the boundary between the Proterozoic and the [[Phanerozoic]] eons was set at the base of the [[Cambrian]] [[period (geology)|Period]] when the first fossils of animals including [[trilobite]]s and [[archaeocyatha|archeocyathids]] appeared. In the second half of the 20th century, a number of fossil forms have been found in Proterozoic rocks, but the upper boundary of the Proterozoic has remained fixed at the base of the Cambrian, which is currently placed at 541&nbsp;Ma.
